@jonfreeman9682  It's 100% true.  They don't put films out in theaters to lose $80 million.  It's not gravy when you have to make up nearly $100 million lol.  

Explain how they make back $80 million?  I asked once and you didn't give me anything.  Just because they put Predator Badlands on Disney+ doesn't mean they put $80M back in their pocket.  That's nonsense.  You think $80 million worth of subscribers are going to sign up for D+ because they put Predator Badlands on there?  Nope! 

You don't invest $150 million in a film hoping to possibly break even years down the road on streaming.  If the film broke even in theaters maybe I could see  your point, but it lost nearly $100 million!  That's bad business.  Good business would be to not spend so much on a Predator film so the break even point is more achievable.  Or invest in a project that doesn't lose $100 million at the box office.  You're doing a lot of mental gymnastics to excuse losing $100 million at the box office.  That's a lot of $4.99 rentals.....

@ZachFazio-v3y  Well on the surface yes I would agree.  I thought the same as you.  But then I look at Netflix spending $200 million on Red Notice (very bad despite big names) and $300 million on Electric State both with zero box office and they are immensely successful.  Netflix has the opportunity to release their movies theatrically like Frankenstein, rated highly by fans and critics, but only gave it a limited run probably for awards eligibility but don't really care about box office.  It's small change to them.  The old business model was make a movie then cash in at the box office.  Then earn on digital rentals and sales.  Then earn on licensing to other networks.  The new business model is build your exclusive content library and add as many subscribers as possible.  Any box office and digital rentals and sales are just gravy.  Amazon and Apple are doing the same thing though Apple did give F1 a big theatrical release.  That's why they can afford to spend hundreds of millions on TV shows with zero box office but adds subscribers and enhances retention with their weekly release schedules and multiple seasons rather than a one shot movie.

Keep in mind this revenue model is not unique to movies and shows.  Microsoft is actively buying out game companies to build their game pass subscribers competing with Sony's game pass.  Because of their scale it gives them a big advantage over smaller players like Electronic Arts also doing their own game pass and was just bought out by private equity.  So it's all about scale and subscriptions and locking you into their ecosystem.  Apple Amazon Google excels at this and Microsoft is doing the same giving you Windows 11 free (like iOS and Android) then getting you on their subscription plan plus collecting user data to monetize advertising potential and giving Bing a huge boost.  This is similar to the free to play gaming model to bring in as many players as possible then cash in on upsells vs just selling a game.

You see why box office isn't as important as in the past.  It's like selling a piece of software once but that's it for income.  Why not lock in a subscriber and create a recurring monthly revenue stream.  If you look at the share price of companies with this business model it's thru the roof with ridiculous valuations.  That's why Netflix and Paramount are trying to buyout WB for its content and IP but especially subscribers.  Don't get me wrong.  Box office revenue is nice but it's not make or break for big studios.  I do hope cinema survive though.
